---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Waltz — Igor Khokhriakov"
  description="A pluggable web frontend for SCADA control systems, built in 2016 when almost no facility had one. Three artifacts outlived it: a reliable SSE event-source library, an event-bus SPA middleware, and a framework-agnostic plugin model."
>
  <Nav />
  <main>
    <article class="container case-study">

      <header class="cs-header">
        <p class="section-marker">Case study · pioneered 2016</p>
        <h1>A web interface for control systems, before control systems had one.</h1>
        <p class="cs-lead">
          In 2016, almost no scientific facility ran a browser-based interface to its
          control system; operators sat at native desktop clients wired to the hardware.
          Waltz was among the first to put that interface in a browser, for accelerators,
          synchrotrons, and neutron sources running Tango Controls and other middlewares.
          Building it early meant solving problems the ecosystem had no patterns for yet,
          and three of those solutions outlived the application itself.
        </p>
        <div class="cs-links">
          <a href="https://github.com/scientific-software-hub/waltz" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[source]</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/orgs/waltz-controls/packages" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[packages]</a>
          <a href="https://waltz-docs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[docs]</a>
          <a href="https://accelconf.web.cern.ch/icalepcs2019/papers/wesh3003.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[paper: ICALEPCS 2019]</a>
        </div>
      </header>

      <section class="cs-section">
        <h2>What outlived the app</h2>
        <p>
          A web application is rarely the durable part of an engineering effort. The durable
          parts of Waltz were the libraries underneath it, each one a solution to a problem
          that had no off-the-shelf answer in 2016, each published and reusable independently
          of the host application.
        </p>

        <h3>A reliable Server-Sent Events source</h3>
        <p>
          Control systems push a continuous stream of attribute changes; an operator UI that
          polls for them does not scale and does not stay current. The browser's native
          <code>EventSource</code> reconnects, but it does not recover missed events, dedupe
          across reconnects, or multiplex many logical subscriptions over one connection.
          The SSE event-source library solved those gaps so the rest of the application could
          treat a live hardware stream as a dependable feed rather than a best-effort one.
        </p>
        <div class="cs-proof">
          <a href="https://github.com/orgs/waltz-controls/packages" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[@waltz-controls/eventbus]</a>
        </div>

        <h3>An event-bus SPA middleware</h3>
        <p>
          Rather than adopt a heavyweight framework, Waltz runs on a thin middleware built
          around a central event-browser object: an internal bus that routes messages between
          independently developed components. Components never call each other directly; they
          publish and subscribe. That decoupling is what later made framework-agnostic plugins
          possible, because a plugin only needs to speak the bus protocol, not share the host's
          component model.
        </p>
        <div class="cs-proof">
          <a href="https://github.com/orgs/waltz-controls/packages" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[@waltz-controls/middleware]</a>
        </div>

        <h3>A framework-agnostic plugin model</h3>
        <p>
          Widgets register against the bus at startup and resolve at render time. Because the
          contract is the message protocol rather than a shared component base class, widgets
          written in different frameworks coexist in one running application: the production
          build ships Webix widgets, CodeMirror, and Plotly side by side, and the same model
          accommodates React or Angular widgets without changing core code. A facility adds its
          own instrument widget without forking the platform, and that widget survives the next
          upstream release because nothing in core imports it.
        </p>
        <div class="cs-proof">
          <a href="https://github.com/orgs/waltz-controls/packages" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[@waltz-controls/tango-rest-client]</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/waltz-controls" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[GitHub org]</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="cs-section">
        <h2>The boundary contract</h2>
        <p>
          Underneath the plugin model sits the Tango REST API specification, written as a formal
          document before the server code that implemented it. Any conforming server worked with
          Waltz; any conforming client worked with any conforming server. The spec was adopted
          across the Tango Controls community as the standard interface between web clients and
          control systems. This is the same instinct as the <code>strategy_spec.json</code> in
          the trading platform: when components deploy independently, the boundary is a
          documented data contract, not shared code.
        </p>
        <div class="cs-proof">
          <a href="https://github.com/tango-controls/rest-api" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[Tango REST spec]</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="cs-section">
        <h2>Leaving the method behind</h2>
        <p>
          Three workshops at DESY in 2019 brought developers from multiple facilities together to
          build extensions collaboratively. The goal was not adoption metrics; it was making sure
          maintainers elsewhere could diagnose and fix issues without routing everything through
          the original author. The architecture made that possible because the libraries and the
          plugin contract were independently documented and independently versioned.
        </p>
        <div class="cs-proof">
          <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rKnVGFP_VCA" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[video: Workshop I]</a>
          <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=npj8paRuF0Q" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[video: Workshop II]</a>
          <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2ryBt_Cztb0" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[video: Workshop III]</a>
          <a href="https://vimeo.com/268669625" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="proof-link">[video: UI overview 2018]</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="cs-section">
        <h2>Numbers</h2>
        <div class="cs-numbers">
          <div class="cs-num">
            <span class="metric cs-num-val">2016</span>
            <span class="cs-num-label">among the first web SCADA UIs</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-num">
            <span class="metric cs-num-val">10</span>
            <span class="cs-num-label">years active development</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-num">
            <span class="metric cs-num-val">50</span>
            <span class="cs-num-label">releases</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-num">
            <span class="metric cs-num-val">757</span>
            <span class="cs-num-label">commits</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="cs-section">
        <h2>Stack</h2>
        <p class="mono" style="color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.85rem;">
          JavaScript · RxJS · Webix · CodeMirror · Plotly · webpack · Server-Sent Events ·
          REST · Docker · Tomcat · Tango Controls · EPICS · TINE · DOOCS
        </p>
      </section>

      <footer class="cs-footer">
        <p>
          What this demonstrates: solving infrastructure problems before the ecosystem has
          patterns for them, and packaging the solutions so they outlast the application that
          motivated them. The web app was the occasion; the SSE library, the event-bus
          middleware, and the plugin contract were the lasting work.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
          <a href="/" class="mono">← Back to home</a>
          <span style="margin-inline: 1rem; color: var(--border)">·</span>
          <a href="/trading-platform/" class="mono">Trading platform case study →</a>
        </p>
      </footer>

    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>

<style>
  .case-study { padding-block: clamp(3rem, 8vw, 5rem); }

  .cs-header {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
    padding-bottom: 3rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .cs-header h1 { margin-block: 1rem 1.25rem; max-width: 24ch; }
  .cs-lead { color: var(--muted); font-size: 1.05rem; margin-top: 0; text-align: justify; }

  .cs-links { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 1.25rem; }

  .cs-section {
    margin-bottom: 2.75rem;
    padding-bottom: 2.75rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .cs-section:last-of-type { border-bottom: none; }
  .cs-section h2 { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .cs-section h3 { margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text); }
  .cs-section p { text-align: justify; }

  .cs-proof { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 0.75rem; }

  .cs-numbers {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(130px, 1fr));
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
  .cs-num { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.25rem; }
  .cs-num-val {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-stretch: expanded;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.5rem);
    line-height: 1;
  }
  .cs-num-label {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .cs-footer {
    padding-top: 2.5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
  .cs-footer p:first-child { text-align: justify; }
</style>
